        <div n="991A07H1" type="poem"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"/></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">T</hi>O fair lady <hi rend="underline">Betty Dan</hi> sat for his picture,</l><l n="2" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-2"> And defy'd her to draw him so oft as he <hi rend="underline">piqu'd</hi> her,</l><l n="3" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-3"> He knew she'd no pencil or colouring by her,</l><l n="4" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-4"> And therefore he thought he might safely defy her.</l><l n="5" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-5"> Come sit, says my lady, then whips up her scissar,</l><l n="6" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-6"> And cuts out his coxcomb in silk in a trice, Sir.<hi rend="underline">Dan</hi> sat with attention, and saw with surprize</l><l n="7" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-7"> How she lengthen'd his chin, how she hollow'd his eyes,</l><l n="8" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-8"> But flatter'd himself with a secret conceit,</l><l n="9" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-9"> That his thin leathern jaws all her art wou'd defeat.</l><l n="10" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-10"> Lady <hi rend="underline">Betty</hi> observ'd it, then pulls out a pin,</l><l n="11" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-11"> And varies the grain of the stuff to his grin;</l><l n="12" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-12"> And to make roasted silk to resemble his raw-bone,</l><l n="13" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-13"> She rais'd up a thread to the jett of his jaw-bone;</l><l n="14" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-14"> Till at length in exactest proportion he rose,</l><l n="15" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-15"> From the crown of his head to the arch of his nose.</l><l n="16" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-16"> And if lady <hi rend="underline">Betty</hi> had drawn him with wig and all,</l><l n="17" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-17"> 'Tis certain the copy had out-done the original.Well, that's but my outside, says <hi rend="underline">Dan</hi> with a vapour.</l><l n="18" xml:id="spp-991A07H1-line-18" rend="flush right"> Say you so? says my lady; I've lin'd it with paper.P──────D──────<hi rend="underline">sculpsit</hi>.991A07H1   </l></lg></div>
